<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0134</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Association of Employment and Learning Providers – Written evidence</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This is a </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">submission from the Association of Employment and Learning Providers to the Joint Parliamentary Committee on the draft Deregulation Bill.</span></p><h1 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></h1><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Association of Employment and Learning Providers (AELP) </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">represents</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> the interests of a range of organisations delivering state-funded vocational learning – our members deliver in excess of 70% of all Apprenticeships.  The majority of our 640+ member organisations are independent providers (from both the private and the third sectors) holding contracts with the Skills Funding Agency, but many also deliver Department of Work and Pensions (DWP) provision.  In addition to these we have a number of colleges in membership, as well as non-delivery organisations such as Sectors Skills Councils (SSCs) and awarding bodies as Associate Members, which means that AELP offers a well rounded and comprehensive perspective and insight on matters relating to its remit.  </span></li></ol><h1 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AELP’s views on the draft Deregulation Bill</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The further education (FE) and skills proposals in the draft Bill include measures to implement the Richard review of apprenticeships.  Whilst AELP supports the main objective of the review – ensuring employer ‘ownership’ of the apprenticeship programme, so that apprenticeship numbers increase and more employers recruit and employ apprentices – we do believe that employers are already firmly in control of the existing apprenticeship programme.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Apprenticeships are a success story</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> but action could be taken to make the apprenticeship system more effective as its responsiveness to employers’ needs could be considerably improved.  We have on many occasions put forward recommendations to improve the system; these include proposals relating to procurement and in year contract adjustments to incentivise employer demand and flexibility of delivery.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Many of the measures in the draft Bill are required to remove the Specification of Apprenticeship Standards for England (SASE) so that the Richard review proposals can be implemented. Whilst we had some reservations about SASE when it was introduced, believing that the standards would not in themselves automatically improve the overall quality of apprenticeships, they have been in place for some time now, and we believe it would be more appropriate to properly evaluate their impact and effectiveness before taking any action to remove or change them.   </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The removal of all restrictions and standards without such an evaluation could lead to a free for all that would undermine the quality of some apprenticeships, seriously damage reputation of the programme and result in the numbers of employers and apprentices involved declining.  Individual employers must not be given complete freedom to design </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">an apprenticeship solely around their own requirements.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Whilst we would welcome changes that would increase the responsiveness of apprenticeships to the needs of employers a number of features must be retained or enhanced going forward:</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Apprenticeships must remain real jobs;</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:3.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Employers should continue to identify what outcomes they require of an apprenticeship and use these to specify out what vocational standards and competencies should form part of the programme’s framework.  They do need to involve providers in the process, however, to ensure the programme is deliverable in the workplace;</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14pt; padding-left:3.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Greater diversity and innovation should be allowed in delivering apprenticeships, unnecessary prescription and regulation should be stripped out, and a more flexible ‘core and options’ approach developed so that provision can be tailored to the needs of both the individual and their employer.  The agreed outcome must be the achievement of the employer required competencies for the occupation covered by the apprenticeship and there should be no requirement for an apprentice to demonstrate again a competence that has already been achieved and accredited as they progress to a higher level; </span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The end product of an apprenticeship must be a fully rounded apprentice, with the competencies required to do the job.  We should move away from stipulating the processes to achieve this, and focus on the outcomes, giving professional training providers (or the employer if they wish to deliver their apprenticeships themselves) the freedom to find the best way to do this; and </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">For the FE system to be fully effective all government funded skills development programmes should be delivered by those providers best equipped and most able to do so.  The FE system must therefore be fully open to all types of provider, chosen solely on their capacity to deliver high quality provision.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Finally, we are concerned that the changes proposed by the Bill will lead to an even greater disparity between apprenticeships across the different parts of the UK, causing additional problems to national employers working in both England and the devolved administrations.</span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">AELP supports the aim of making apprenticeships more flexible and responsive to the needs of employers and the economy, but believes the removal of SASE requirements without a comprehensive evaluation of the standards’ impact and effectiveness first would be a mistake.  Great care is needed before making sweeping changes that could damage the reputation of apprenticeships and lead to a dramatic decline in the number of employers and apprentices involved.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Over 200,000 workplaces have participated, over half a million new apprentices started and success rates nationally at 73.8%, similar to average completion rates for a full-time degree programme.</span></p></body></html>